        <introduction>
            <p>
                There are proofs of several statements below that assume the following definitions: 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\tan(x) = \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sec(x) = \frac{1}{\cos(x)}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A number <m>n</m> is even if there exists an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>n=2k</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A number <m>n</m> is odd if there exists an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>n=2k + 1</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                For each proof, identify (with explanation)
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            the <term>good</term> (is anything done well?),
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            the <term>bad</term> (is anything mathematically incorrect?),
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            the <term>ugly</term> (is anything difficult to read/follow?).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <claim>
            <statement>
                   <p>
                        <m>\tan^2(x) = \sec^2(x) - 1</m>
                    </p>         
            </statement>
            <proof>
                    <p>
                      Note
                        <md>
                            \tan^2(x) = \sec^2(x) - 1
                        </md>
                        <md>
                            \implies \frac{\sin^2(x)}{\cos^2(x)} = \frac{1}{\cos^2(x)}-1 
                        </md>
                        <md>
                            \implies \frac{\sin^2(x)}{\cos^2(x)} = \frac{1- \cos^2(x)}{\cos^2(x)}
                        </md>
                        <md>
                            \implies \sin^2(x) = 1- \cos^2(x)
                        </md>
                        <md>
                            \implies \sin^2(x)+ \cos^2(x) = 1
                        </md>
                        
                        
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Since the last equality is known to be true, the first equality must also be true. 
                    
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                       <m> \hspace{15cm} \blacksquare</m>
                    </p> 
                    
            </proof>
        </claim>
            
        <claim>
            <statement>
                   <p>
                        The sum of two even integers is even.
                    </p>         
            </statement>
            <proof>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>a=2m</m>, <m>b=2n</m>.
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        <m>a+b = 2m + 2n \implies 2(m+n)</m>, which is even.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                       <m> \hspace{15cm} \blacksquare</m>
                    </p> 
                    
            </proof>
        </claim>

        <claim>
            <statement>
                   <p>
                        Let <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m>. If <m>x^2=0</m>, then <m>x=0</m>.
                    </p>         
            </statement>
            <proof>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> and <m>x^2 =0</m>. Then clearly <m>x=0</m>.
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                       <m> \hspace{15cm} \blacksquare</m>
                    </p> 
                    
            </proof>
        </claim>

        <claim>
            <statement>
                   <p>
                        The square of an odd integer is also odd.
                    </p>         
            </statement>
            <proof>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>n</m> be an odd integer. Then for some integer <m>k</m>,
                      <md>
                        n=2k+1 = 4k^2 + 4k + 1
                      </md>,
                      which is odd.
                      
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                       <m> \hspace{15cm} \blacksquare</m>
                    </p> 
                    
            </proof>
        </claim>

        <claim>
            <statement>
                   <p>
                        Every constant function is a continuous function.
                    </p>         
            </statement>
            <proof>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>f</m> be the constant function <m>f(x) = 5</m>. Then <m>f</m> is a horizontal line at 
                      <m>5</m>, which can be sketched without picking up your pencil. Therefore, they are continuous.
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                       <m> \hspace{15cm} \blacksquare</m>
                    </p> 
                    
            </proof>
        </claim>


